'''''Juego de maní''''' ('game of war') often simply called '''''maní''''' or '''''mani''''', sometimes referred to as '''''baile de maní''''' ('dance of war') or '''''bambosa''''',<ref name="Ortiz, Fernando 1951">{{cite book |title=Los bailes y el teatro de los negros en el folklore de Cuba |trans-title=The Dances and the Theatre of the Negros in the Folklore of Cuba |last=Ortiz |first=Fernando |year=1951 |publisher=Ediciones Cárdenas y Cia |language=Spanish |isbn=978-8489750210}}</ref> is a combined [[martial art]] and [[dance]] that was developed in [[Cuba]] by [[Atlantic slave trade|African slaves]]. It has its roots in the [[Kongo people|Kongo]]-[[Angola]] culture and is still kept alive today in Cuba by folkloric groups. Practitioners are referred to as ''maniseros''.<ref name="Lopes">{{cite book |title=Enciclopédia brasileira da diáspora africana |last=Lopes |first=Nei |year=2004 |publisher = Selo Negro |page=62 |isbn=85-87478-21-4}}</ref>
==Etymology== The word ''mani'' (or accented ''maní'' in Spanish to indicate stress on the final syllable) is said to mean 'war',<ref name="Ortiz, Fernando 1951" /><ref name="Quijano" /> in an indeterminate African language, and is not a reference to 'peanuts', which the word ''maní'' can also refer to in [[Cuban Spanish]].<ref name="Quijano">{{cite web |url= http://www.shiaimagazine.net/news/7-articles-and-interviews/17-miguel-quijano.html |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120606114817/http://www.shiaimagazine.net/news/7-articles-and-interviews/17-miguel-quijano.html |archivedate=June 6, 2012 |title=Miguel Quijano |work=Shiai Magazine |date=September 29, 2010 |accessdate=December 25, 2011 |first=Henry Aurélien |last=Obama}} Detailed interview with a contemporary instructor.</ref> Its longer Spanish names, ''juego de maní'',<ref name="Quijano" /> ('game of ''mani''<nowiki />' or '<nowiki />''maní'' game') and ''baile de maní''<ref name="Ortiz, Fernando 1951" /> ('dance of ''mani''<nowiki />' or '<nowiki />''maní'' dance') would thus mean 'war game' or 'war dance', respectively, when fully translated from both languages.
An even longer name recorded is ''juego de maní con grasa'' (loosely, '<nowiki />''maní'' greased game' or 'war game with grease') because of its smooth and slippery qualities.<ref name="Ortiz, Fernando 1951" />
In English, some modern practitioners call it simply '''mani''', with no accent.<ref name="Quijano" /> The descriptive term '''mani stick-fighting''' may also be encountered.<ref name="MAFSAW">{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=pzDTYdi9RnwC&pg=PA338&dq=Mani+stick+fighting&hl=en&sa=X&ei=x-T3TqfzFKixiQL-7sXHDg&ved=0CEQQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Mani%20stick%20fighting&f=false | title=The Way of the Warrior: Martial Arts and Fighting Styles from Around the World |publisher=DK Publishing |date=2008 |accessdate=December 25, 2011 |last1=Crudelli |first1=Chris |last2=Ross |first2=Chris}} Note that this source spells it both "stick fighting" and "stick-fighting" on the same page.</ref>
== History == Cuban ''juego de maní'' is related to Brazilian ''[[capoeira]]'' in its African roots, as both derive from the [[Kongo people|Kongo]]-[[Angola]] culture.{{citation needed|date=June 2014|reason=try Oritz or Lopes}} As with other similar dance and martial artforms arising in the 16th century onward among [[Transatlantic slave trade|African slaves]] in [[European colonization of the Americas|European colonies in the Americas]], ''juego de maní'' developed initially as means for the slaves to disguise fighting practice as a form of dance, in their scarce free time from labor. Some of their masters would recognize it as fighting competition and gamble on the outcomes.<ref name="Quijano" /><ref name="MAFSAW" /> It is thought that sometimes slaves were made to fight to the death for their masters' sport.<ref name="MAFSAW" />
The distinct Cuban ''juego de maní'' form had emerged clearly by the 19th century on Cuban sugar-cane plantations,<ref name="MAFSAW" /> by then staffed by free people of mixed [[Afro-Cuban]] ancestry.
Originally, Cuban women also danced ''juego de maní'', and this was outlawed in the 1930s, but was still performed.<ref name="Ortiz, Fernando 1951" /><ref name="Daniel 2005">{{cite book |title=Dancing Wisdom: Embodied Knowledge in Haitian Vodou, Cuban Yoruba, and Bahian Candomblé |last=Daniel |first=Yvonne |year=2005 |publisher=University of Illinois Press |page=62 |isbn=0-252-07207-3}}</ref>
Today, ''maní'' is very folkloric, and those who practice it do so mainly as a pastime or for socializing, because it encompasses so much: music, singing, sparring, friendship, etc.
Caricao{{clarify|date=June 2014|reason=No such place. If Curaçao is meant, this is dubious, because it's on the far southern end of the Caribbean.}} has a version, and [[Puerto Rico]] has its own ''maní'' which should not be confused with Cuba's ''juego de maní''.<ref>{{cite book |title=Biography of a Runaway Slave |last1=Montejo |first1=Esteban |last2=Barnet |first2=Miguel |last3=Hill |first3=W. Nick |year=1994 |publisher=University of Texas Press |isbn=1-880684-18-7}}</ref>{{verify source|date=June 2014}}
== Form, techniques, and music ==
Bouts feature a pair of opponents who follow prescribed dancing and fighting patterns, in a circle.<ref name="MAFSAW" /> In early [[Cuba#Colonial Cuba|colonial Cuba]], ''maní'' involved a solo dancer who danced within a circle of opponents, who tried to strike blows as he executed various jumps and evasive steps.{{citation needed|date=June 2014|reason=try Oritz or Lopes}} It later became a one-on-one form.
Although not as [[gymnastic]] as [[Capoeira#Capoeira Regional|''capoeira regional'']], it is much more similar to [[Capoeira#Capoeira Angola|''capoeira Angola'']], and to ''l'agya'' (a.k.a. ''damaye'' or ''mayolé'') from [[Martinique]] and [[Guadeloupe]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Ring of Liberation: Deceptive Discourse in Brazilian Capoeira |last1=Lewis |first1=John Lowell |year=1992 |publisher=University of Chicago Press |isbn=0-226-47682-0}}</ref> The footwork is similar in theory to the Brazilian ''[[Ginga (capoeira)|ginga]]'', but has a more stomping motion.
The combat system of ''maní'' encompasses techniques such as low kicks,{{citation needed|date=June 2014|reason=try Oritz or Lopes}} [[Sweep (martial arts)|foot sweeps]],<ref name="MAFSAW" /> [[Punch (strike)|punches]],<ref name="MAFSAW" /> [[head-butt]]s,<ref name="MAFSAW" /> [[elbow strikes]],<ref name="MAFSAW" /> and strikes with the forearms, knees, and palms,{{citation needed|date=June 2014|reason=for forearms, knees, palms; try Oritz or Lopes}} as well as the [[Cartwheel (gymnastics)|cartwheel]].{{citation needed|date=June 2014|reason=try Oritz or Lopes}} Each fight ends in a sweep, take down or grappling maneuver.{{citation needed|date=June 2014|reason=try Oritz or Lopes}}
''Maní'' may also use weapons such as a cane staff<ref name="MAFSAW" /> (used similarly to those of ''[[calinda]]''-style [[stick-fighting]] in [[Trinidad]] and other Caribbean locales), as well as [[Knife-fighting|knives]],<ref name="MAFSAW" /> including the [[machete]] and double machete.{{citation needed|date=June 2014|reason=try Oritz or Lopes}} The stick used is about the thickness of a [[sugar cane]]<ref name="MAFSAW" /> (whether made of that traditional material or not), and about 16&nbsp;inches (40&nbsp;cm) long.<ref name="MAFSAW" /> The original martial art form of ''juego de maní'' risked particular danger, because the dancer/fighter sometimes wore leather wrist covers, ''muñequeras'', that were adorned with nails and other sorts of metal.{{citation needed|date=June 2014|reason=try Oritz or Lopes}}
The rhythm of the dance/fight is based on the rhythm that is played by the musicians, and accompanying musicians are expected to synchronize drumming accents with movement accents in the performance. This form was popular in [[Matanzas Province|Matanzas]] and [[Santa Clara Province|Las Villas]] [[Provinces of Cuba|provinces]] and featured circling, competitive male dancing, which influenced non-combative, social dances that were created in Cuba, such as ''[[Cuban rumba#Rumba columbia|rumba Columbia]]''.{{citation needed|date=June 2014|reason=try Oritz or Lopes}}
The music utilized in ''juego de maní'' is that of [[Palo (religion)|Palo Monte]], or simply Palo, an Afro-Cuban religion. One of the most popular ''maní'' songs is "''Vamos a la guerra si maní''" ('We go to war if [there is] ''maní''<nowiki />').{{citation needed|date=June 2014|reason=try Oritz or Lopes}}
==''Maniseros''== Skilled practitioners are called ''{{lang|es|maniseros}}''.<ref name="Lopes" /><ref name="Quijano" /> A grandmaster of the art<ref name="Daniel 1995">{{cite book |title=Rumba: Dance and Social Change in Contemporary Cuba |last=Daniel |first=Yvonne |year=1995 |publisher=Indiana University Press |isbn=978-0-253-20948-1 }}</ref> who still teaches in Cuba is Juan de Dios Ramos Morejón, the founder-director of Cuban folkloric dance company Raices Profundas ('Deep Roots').<ref name="Quijano" /><ref name="Daniel 1995" /> De Dios grew up fighting in the streets of Cuba and he has been called a "living encyclopedia" of the art, when he chooses to teach it.<ref name="Daniel 1995" /> He has been an ambassador of Afro-Cuban music and martial arts for many years, having traveled to teach in places as diverse as [[Germany]], [[Japan]], the [[United States]], and [[Mexico]].<ref name="Daniel 1995" /> His Puerto Rican New Yorker protegé Miguel Quijano (a current mani teacher and instructional author) notes De Dios as also a ''[[Santería|santero]]'', and a ceremonial singer "versed in Yoruba, Palo, Abakua, and Arara traditions, known throughout Cuba".<ref name="Quijano" />
De Dios was in turn a student, with seven others, of the great ''manisero'' Argeliers Leon.<ref name="Quijano" /> Quijano writes of the eight graduates of Leon that they "knew the art ... in its entirety", as both a dance form and a martial art,<ref name="Quijano" /> and were founding members of the Conjunto Folklorico Nacional (Cuba's 'National Folkloric Connection' dance organization),<ref name="Quijano" /><ref name="Daniel 1995" /> where they taught "a folkloric version", i.e. one oriented to dance performance.<ref name="Quijano" />
It is through these folklorical groups that Palo and ''maní'' are kept alive. Although a few masters still exist in Cuba, not many truly understand the fighting aspects of the art over the folkloric dance version.<ref name="Daniel 1995" /> According to Quijano, who has studied under several of them, the only living master ''maniseros'' are Juan de Dios, Carlos Aldama, and Rogelio Martinez Fure (he also counts Cuban journalist Alberto Pedro, but as a retired practitioner).<ref name="Quijano" />
