'''Julia Maesa''' (7 May before 160 AD - {{circa|224}} AD) was a 3rd century  [[List of Augustae|Augusta]] (empress) of the [[Roman Empire]] and a powerful, prominent and influential figure in the empire's politics during the rule of the [[Severan dynasty]]. Born in [[Homs|Emesa]], [[Roman Syria|Syria]] (modern day [[Homs]]), Maesa was the daughter of the high priest of [[Great Mosque of al-Nuri (Homs)|Emesa's Temple of the Sun]], and the elder sister of future Roman empress [[Julia Domna]].

Through her sister's marriage, she became sister-in law to the emperor [[Septimius Severus]] and later the aunt of emperors [[Caracalla]] and [[Geta (emperor)|Geta]]. She herself married fellow Syrian [[Julius Avitus]], who was of consular rank.{{sfn|Grant|1996|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=sCYMAm1k4KwC&pg=PA47 47]}}{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA207 207]}} She bore him two daughters, [[Julia Soaemias]] and [[Julia Mamaea]],{{sfn|Salisbury|2001|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=HF0m3spOebcC&pg=PA183 183]}} who would later became mothers of emperors [[Elagabalus]] and [[Severus Alexander]] respectively.{{sfn|Grant|1996|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=sCYMAm1k4KwC&pg=PA47 47]}}

The [[Severan dynasty]] of ancient Rome was dominated by powerful women, one of which was Julia Maesa. Politically able and ruthless, she contended for political power after her sister's suicide.{{sfn|Salisbury|2001|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=HF0m3spOebcC&pg=PA183 183]}} She is best known for her plotting and scheming which resulted in the restoration of the Severan dynasty to the Roman throne after the assassination of Caracalla and the usurpation of the Roman throne by [[Macrinus]],{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA209 209]}} after which she continued to shape and dominate the politics of the Roman Empire for well over two decades, being the major power behind the Roman throne in the subsequent reigns of Elagabalus and Severus Alexander until her death.{{sfn|Salisbury|2001|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=HF0m3spOebcC&pg=PA183 183]}}

Julia Maesa died in Rome at an uncertain date between 223 and 226,{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA217 217]}} and was later deified in Syria along with her sister.{{sfn|Lee|2016|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=RfBWCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA16 16]}}{{sfn|Grant|1996|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=sCYMAm1k4KwC&pg=PA47 47]}}

== Early life and marriage ==
{{double image|right|Perge - Julia Soemias 2.jpg|140|Julia mammea02 pushkin.jpg|130|Maesa's daughters, [[Julia Soaemias]] and [[Julia Mamaea]]}}
Julia Maesa was born in 7 May{{sfn|Lee|2016|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=RfBWCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA16 16]}} before around 160AD, the elder daughter of the priest [[Julius Bassianus]] in [[Homs|Emesa]], [[Roman Syria|Syria]], modern day [[Homs]].{{sfn|Birley|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=GcmEAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA72 72]}} She had a younger sister, [[Julia Domna]] who would later become Roman empress after her marriage to [[Septimius Severus]] who was by the time of their marriage a senator.{{sfn|Levick|2007|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=BjkfKsCttrkC&pg=PA23 23]}}

As she was an [[Arab people|Arab]],{{sfn|Shahid|1984|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=W4H97SA6pMAC&pg=PA33 33]}}{{sfn|Birley|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=GcmEAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA222 222]}} her [[cognomen]], Maesa, is the feminine nomen agentis of the Arabic verb "masa" which signifies walking with a swinging gait.{{sfn|Shahid|1984|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=W4H97SA6pMAC&pg=PA41 41]}}{{sfn|Birley|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=GcmEAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA222 222]}} This would be an appropriate female name as the verb from which it was derived was used by Arab poets to describe the figures of the women that they write about.{{sfn|Shahid|1984|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=W4H97SA6pMAC&pg=PA41 41]}}

She later married a fellow Syrian, [[Julius Avitus]], a consul who also served as provincial governor in the empire.{{sfn|Grant|1996|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=sCYMAm1k4KwC&pg=PA47 47]}} She bore him two daughters, her eldest daughter, [[Julia Soaemias]], was born around 180 AD{{sfn|Kean|2005|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=XFsYAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA120 120]}} or some time before,{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA56 56]}} and was followed by another daughter, [[Julia Mamaea]] not long after.{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA207 207]}}

=== Appearance ===
Although no written account describing her appearance survives, her sharp and formidable features, which contradict the soft and sensitive ones of her sister,{{sfn|Levick|2007|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=BjkfKsCttrkC&pg=PA3 3]}} are well displayed on the coins minted during the reign of her grandchildren.{{sfn|Grant|1996|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=sCYMAm1k4KwC&pg=PA47 47]}}

== Life in Rome ==
{{double image|right|Septimius Severus Glyptothek Munich 357.jpg|200|Caracalla MAN Napoli Inv6033 n01.jpg|200|Busts of Septimius Severus (left) and Caracalla (right)}}
After her sister's arrival to Rome and the beginning of her tenure as empress consort, Maesa, accompanied by her family, traveled to Rome where they took up residence in the imperial court,{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA207 207]}} although her husband, [[Julius Avitus]] who held several important posts did not stay in Rome for long and had to make many travels across the empire, which she did not accompany him on.{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA56 56]}}

During their stay in Rome, she and her family amassed extreme wealth and fortune,{{sfn|Lightman|Lightman|2008|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=2esYJJUETiYC&pg=PA171 171]}} and rose highly in the Roman government and court of [[Septimius Severus]] and later, his son and successor [[Caracalla]].{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA207 207]}} Her two daughters attained a prominent position in court while their Syrian husbands held important posts as provincial governors and consuls,{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA58 58]}}{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA207 207]}} with Maesa's own husband along with that of her daughter rising from the [[Equites|Equestrian rank]] to reach Senatorial rank.{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA58 58]}}

=== Return to Emesa ===
In 217 AD, after the murder of emperor Caracalla and the usurpation of the throne by [[Macrinus]], Maesa's sister, Domna, now with none of the power or influence she held during the reigns of her husband and her son, suffering from breast cancer, and having lost both of her children, chose to commit suicide by starvation.{{sfn|Salisbury|2001|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=HF0m3spOebcC&pg=PA183 183]}}{{sfn|Birley|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=GcmEAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA192 192]}}

Maesa and her family, who had resided in Rome for the last two decades,{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA207 207]}} were spared and ordered by Macrinus to leave Rome and return to their home town of Emesa in Syria,{{sfn|Lightman|Lightman|2008|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=2esYJJUETiYC&pg=PA171 171]}}{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA207 207]}} likely because Macrinus wanted to avoid any action that would seem disloyal to Caracalla's memory to avoid any reprisals from the army.{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA207 207]}} Macrinus made the crucial mistake of leaving Maesa's great wealth, amassed over a period of over 20 years intact,{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA207 207]}}{{sfn|Lightman|Lightman|2008|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=2esYJJUETiYC&pg=PA171 171]}} a decision which Macrinus would regret not long after.{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA56 56]}}

Maesa, who arrived in Emesa sometime between spring 217 and spring 218,{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA58 58]}} vowed revenge,{{sfn|Bunson|2014|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=T5tic2VunRoC&pg=PA193 193]}} and Domna's suicide was still far off from ending the influence of the powerful women of the family.{{sfn|Salisbury|2001|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=HF0m3spOebcC&pg=PA183 183]}}

== Restoration of the Severan dynasty ==
[[File:Julia Domna Glyptothek Munich 354.jpg|thumb|Roman empress [[Julia Domna]], Maesa's sister, committed suicide after the murder of her son Caracalla]]
Macrinus was in a difficult position after Caracalla's assassination and was struggling to gain legitimacy and maintain loyalty to his rule.{{sfn|Birley|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=GcmEAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA192 192]}}{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA207 207]}} This encouraged Maesa, whose location, Emesa, which was close to a military base where many soldiers still held the Severans in high esteem and were loyal to the dynasty,{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA207 207]}} aside from their discontent over Macrinus' peace with the [[Parthian Empire|Parthian]]s,{{sfn|Birley|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=GcmEAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA192 192]}} made it an excellent choice to launch a coup to restore her family to power.{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA207 207]}}

The first step was to choose a male candidate from within the family to replace the usurper.{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA207 207]}} [[Julius Avitus|Maesa's own husband]] has died in Cyprus shortly before 217,{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA207 207]}} as well as her [[Sextus Varius Marcellus|eldest daughter's husband]].{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA207 207]}} Julia Soaemias had a 14-year old son, [[Elagabalus|Varius Avitus Bassianus]], who was the hereditary priest of the Emesan sun god,{{sfn|Birley|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=GcmEAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA192 192]}}{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA207 207]}} and Maesa had a different future in mind for him.{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA207 207]}} He had began attracting the soldiers of the [[Legio III Gallica]] stationed near Emesa, who would visit the city's temple occasionally to view the extravagant yet amusing religious rituals of Bassianus.{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA11 11]}}

Now even further encouraged by the attention of the soldiers, she proceeded with her plot by trying to challenge the legitimacy of the new emperor Macrinus, and she did so by claiming that the 14 year old, who greatly resembled Caracalla, was indeed the former emperor's bastard son and that Caracalla slept with both her daughters.{{sfn|Lightman|Lightman|2008|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=2esYJJUETiYC&pg=PA171 171]}}{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA209 209]}} The claim that Bassianus was the love child of Caracalla and Soaemias, despite almost certainly being untrue,{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA11 11]}} was not so easily refuted, as aside from the young boy's resemblance to the emperor,{{sfn|Lightman|Lightman|2008|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=2esYJJUETiYC&pg=PA171 171]}} Soaemias had been living in the Roman court at the time of Caracalla's reign,{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA209 209]}} and Maesa seemed not to mind that this claim would be sacrificing the honor and reputation of her daughters as it was, after all, an effective move to further her plan.{{sfn|Halsberghe|1972|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=8tIUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA60 60]}}

Julia Maesa began offering to distribute her great wealth and fortune to the loyal soldiers in exchange for their support,{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA209 209]}} news of which began to spread throughout the army camps.{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA11 11]}} Maesa, her daughter and Bassianus were taken into the army camp at night where the 14 year old boy was immediately acknowledged and hailed as emperor by the soldiers and clad in imperial purple.{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA11 11]}}

Historian [[Cassius Dio]] narrates a slightly different version of events; he mentions a certain [[Gannys]], who is not mentioned as partaking in the plot at any other source, as the main instigator of the revolt.{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA11 11]}} Allegedly a 'youth who has not yet reached manhood', Dio claims he was raised by Maesa and was Soaemias' lover and the protector of her son,{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA11 11]}} and at a certain night, dressed Bassianus in clothes worn by Caracalla as a child, took him to the army camp and claimed he was the murdered emperor's son without the knowledge of either Soaemias or Maesa.{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA11 11]}}

It is hard to believe that Maesa and Soaemias, with much to gain from the young boy becoming emperor, would be completely unaware of the actions of Gannys.{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA11 11]}} On the other hand, it's also unlikely that Maesa alone orchestrated the young boy's ascension. It's likely that Maesa in her plan had the support of many important figures from the city of Emesa and even some figures in Rome's ruling elite.{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA11 11]}}

=== Reaction of Macrinus ===
[[File:Aureus Macrinus-RIC 0079 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|175px|[[Macrinus]], who usurped the Roman throne in 217 AD]]
With the support of an entire legion, other legionnaires, prompted by discontent over pay, deserted Macrinus and joined Elagabalus' ranks as well. In response to the growing threat, Macrinus sent out a cavalry force under the command of Ulpius Julianus to try and regain control of the rebel soldiers. Rather than capturing the rebel forces, the cavalry instead killed Ulpius and defected to Elagabalus.{{sfn|Gibbon|1961|p=183}}{{sfn|Mennen|2011|p=165}}

Following these events, Macrinus traveled to [[Apamea, Syria|Apamea]] to ensure the loyalty of [[Legio II Parthica|Legio II ''Parthica'']] before setting off to march against Emesa.{{sfn|Downey|1961|pp=249–250}} According to Dio, Macrinus appointed his son Diadumenian to the position of [[Imperator]], and promised the soldiers 20,000 Sesterces each, with 4,000 of these to be paid on the spot. Dio further says that Macrinus hosted a dinner for the residents of Apamea in honour of Diadumenian.{{sfn|Dio|1927|p=417}}{{sfn|Dio|1927|loc=79.34.3}} At the dinner, Macrinus was supposedly presented with the head of Ulpius Julianus who had been killed by his soldiers.{{sfn|Dio|1927|p=417}}{{sfn|Dio|1927|loc=79.34.4}} In response, Macrinus left Apamea and headed south.{{sfn|Downey|1961|pp=249–250}}

Macrinus' and Elagabalus' troops met somewhere near the border of [[Syria Coele (Roman province)|Syria Coele]] and [[Phoenice (Roman province)|Syria Phoenice]]. Despite Macrinus' efforts to quell the rebellion at this engagement, his whole legion defected to Elagabalus forcing Macrinus to retire to [[Antioch]]. Elagabus took to the offensive and marched on Antioch.{{sfn|Downey|1961|pp=249–250}}

==== Battle of Antioch ====
{{main|Battle of Antioch (218)}}
Elagabalus' armies, commanded by the inexperienced but determined [[Gannys]], engaged Macrinus' Praetorian Guard in a narrowly fought [[pitched battle]].{{sfn|Gibbon|1961|p=184}} Gannys commanded at least two full legions and held numerical superiority over the fewer levies that Macrinus had been able to raise. Macrinus had ordered the Praetorian Guard to set aside their scaled armour breastplates and grooved shields in favour of lighter oval shields prior to the battle. This made them lighter and more manoeuvrable and negated any advantage light Parthian lancers had.{{sfn|Dio|1927|p=425}}{{sfn|Dio|1927|loc=79.37.4}} The Praetorian Guards broke through the lines of Gannys' force, which turned to flee. During the retreat, however, Julia Maesa and Soaemias, in a surprising act of heroism joined the fray, leaping from their chariots to rally the retreating forces,{{sfn|Lightman|Lightman|2008|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=2esYJJUETiYC&pg=PA172 172]}} while Gannys charged on horseback headlong into the enemy. These actions effectively ended the retreat; the troops resumed the assault with renewed morale, turning the tide of battle.{{sfn|Gibbon|1961|p=184}}{{sfn|Goldsworthy|2009|pp=78–79}} Fearing defeat, Macrinus fled back to the city of Antioch,{{sfn|Downey|1961|pp=249–250}} attempting escape before being executed in [[Cappadocia]],{{sfn|Crevier|1814|p=237}}{{sfn|Bell|1834|p=229}} while his son [[Diadumenian]] was captured en route in [[Zeugma]], and executed as well.{{sfn|Vagi|2000|p=290}}

Elagablus entered Antioch as its emperor, refraining the soldiers from sacking the city and sending a message to the senate who were forced to accept the young boy as their new emperor.{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA14 14]}} Upon ascension he took up the name ''Marcus Aurelius Antoninus Augustus''.{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA55 55]}}

== Reign of Elagabalus ==
{{main|Elagabalus}}
[[File:Bust of Elagabalus - Palazzo Nuovo - Musei Capitolini - Rome 2016 (2).jpg|thumb|left|Head of Elagabalus]]
Although now declared emperor, his claim was not uncontested, however, as several others laid claim to the Roman Throne. These included Verus the commander of [[Legio III Gallica]] who ironically was the first to proclaim Elagabalus as emperor, and Gellius Maximus the commander of Legio IV Scythica. These rebellions were quashed and their instigators executed.{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA14 14]}}

Elagabalus spent the winter of 218-219 in [[Nicomedia]] before he set off to enter [[Rome]].{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA17 17]}} Maesa allegedly urged him to enter the capital draped in Roman clothes, but instead, he had a painting of him made as a priest making offerings to the Emesene deity [[Elagabalus (deity)|El-Gabal]].{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA17 17]}} The painting was hanged right above the statue of [[Victoria (mythology)|Victoria]] in the senate, putting senators in the awkward position of having to make offerings to the Syrian deity whenever they wanted to make offerings to Victoria.<ref>[http://www.livius.org/articles/person/heliogabalus/heliogabalus-2/?#Life1 Heliogabalus (2) - Livius]</ref>

Both Maesa and her daughter Soaemias are featured heavily in all literary accounts of his reign, and are credited with much influence over the young emperor.{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA19 19]}} Julia Maesa was honored with the titles of 'Augusta, mater castrorum et senatus' (empress, mother of the camp and the senate) and 'avia Augusti' (grandmother of the emperor).{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA19 19]}}

Soon, the young emperor was no longer popular with the praetorians, who did not approve of his revolting behavior and his odd religious rituals,{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA37 37]}} and considering how their support was crucial for his rule to survive, this was an extremely dangerous development.{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA37 37]}} Julia Maesa decided to take measures to prevent things from getting too out of hand.{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA37 37]}} She convinced her grandson to adopt his cousin, her grandson [[Severus Alexander|Alexander]], and declare him caesar, with the argument that it would leave more time for Elagabalus to devote himself to religious matters.{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA37 37]}} The adoption of the 12 years old Alexander provided a strategic shift for the supporters of Elagablus,{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA37 37]}} as some of the supporters felt it was no longer wise to tie their fate with that of the priest emperor and saw an alternative in his adopted son.{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA37 37]}}{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA38 38]}}
[[File:Julia Maesa obversee.png|thumb|left|A coin of Julia Maesa from [[Thessaloniki|Thessalonica]] struck during Elagabalus' reign]]
Whatsoever, rivalry was soon increasing between the two boys and Elagabalus regretted adopting his more-popular cousin.{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA39 39]}} The soldiers began to look more favorably upon Elagabalus' cousin, and the allies and supporters of the dynasty as well as the imperial family itself became divided,{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA39 39]}} with Elagabalus and Soaemias on one side, and Mamaea, Maesa and Alexander on the other.{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA214 214]}}

By the beginning of 222, Alexander and Elagabalus became so estranged with each other that they no longer appeared together in public.{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA214 214]}} An assassination attempt against Alexander by Elagabalus enraged the praetorian guards who demanded an assurance for Alexander's safety from Elagabalus and the dismissal of some certain officials.{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA214 214]}} Elagablus broke his promise, prompting the praetorian guard to slay Elagabalus and his mother, cutting their heads off and throwing aside their bodies.{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA214 214]}} Alexander was now proclaimed emperor.{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA214 214]}}

A traditionally held belief is that while the new emperor was mainly involved in religious matters, Julia Maesa and her daughter were the ones effectively running the state.{{sfn|Icks|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-yecRsy847AC&pg=PA19 19]}} This claim has been treated with caution by contemporary historians such as Barabara Levick, as in ancient Rome, politics and religion were intertwined together and the rule of Elagabalus and the supremacy of his deity broke this relationship.{{sfn|Levick|2007|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=BjkfKsCttrkC&pg=PA149 149]}} In any case it's certain that Maesa had influence over the young boy, but Elagabalus' disagreements and neglect of advice from Maesa, who can be presented as an advocate of Roman traditionalism, has been reported and it may well be the cause of his downfall.{{sfn|Levick|2007|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=BjkfKsCttrkC&pg=PA149 149]}}

It is probable that Julia Maesa herself was responsible for the assassination of her daughter and grandson.{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA215 215]}} This would certainly have been a painful sacrifice for Maesa to make but a necessary one to protect her family's grip on power and preserve the empire's stability.{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA215 215]}}

== Reign of Severus Alexander ==
{{main|Severus Alexander}}
[[File:Alexander Severus Musei Capitolini MC471.jpg|thumb|Bust of Severus Alexander]]
Alexander ascended the throne at the age of around 15, and he was kept in check by his mother and grandmother who were determined to erase the negative impression of Elagabalus. He was given the name Marcus Aurelius Severus Alexander to emphasize his relationship to Septimius Severus, the founder of the dynasty.{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA215 215]}}

The epigraphical evidence during Severus Alexander's reign attests that the early years of his reign were dominated by his mother and grandmother, as inscriptions carrying the emperor's name referred to him as ''Juliae Mamaeae Aug(ustae) filio Juliae Maesae Aug(ustae) nepote'' (the son of Julia Mamaea and grandson of Julia Maesa).{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA215 215]}}

The changes introduced by Maesa and her daughter included selecting a council of sixteen chosen for their moderation and experience to advise the young emperor, and the two Julias tried to restore a moderate and dignified form of government.{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA216 216]}}{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA217 217]}} The eastern religious practices introduced by the former emperor were eradicated in Rome and his religious edicts were reversed, the sacred stone of [[Elagabalus (deity)|El-Gabal]] was returned to Emesa and the vast temple which had been dedicated to him by Elagabalus was rededicated to [[Jupiter (mythology)|Jupiter]].{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA215 215]}}

== Death ==
The most certain date of her death is likely between November 224 and 227.{{sfn|McHugh|2017|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=JyIzDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT181 181]}}{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA217 217]}} Her death deprived her daughter, Julia Mamaea, not only of a mother but also of a political mentor and colleague, and Julia Mamaea was now alone in charge of the imperial government.{{sfn|Burns|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hL99AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA217 217]}}

=== Deification ===
Like her sister Julia Domna before her was,{{sfn|Levick|2007|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=BjkfKsCttrkC&pg=PA145 145]}} Julia Maesa was deified.{{sfn|Lee|2016|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=RfBWCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA16 16]}} In the ''[[Feriale Duranum]]'', the list of religious observances of the ''Cohors XX Palmyrenorum'', dating to {{circa|227}} AD,{{sfn|McHugh|2017|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=JyIzDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT181 181]}} Maesa is made a supplication on her birthday which is the 7th of May.{{sfn|Lee|2016|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=RfBWCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA16 16]}} Coins commemorating her deification show her borne aloft on the back of a peacock. Unfortunately the coins are undated, but she also appears deified on the ''[[Acta Fratrum Arvalium]]'' of 7 November in 224, which lists the number of gods and goddesses the ''[[Arval Brethren]]'' made sacrifices to on that certain date.{{sfn|McHugh|2017|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=JyIzDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT181 181]}}

== Legacy ==
There is a hotel in the [[Ancient City of Damascus|Old City of Damascus]] named after the empress.<ref>[http://www.lovedamascus.com/en/where-to-stay/hotels/bab-touma/001ht024/julia-maesa-hotel Julia Maesa Hotel | Hotels in Damascus Old City]</ref>

