{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}} {{Infobox_person |name = Miriam Beizana Vigo |image = |image_upright = |image_size = |birth_name = Miriam Beizana Vigo |birth_date = {{date|20|8|1990|age}} |birth_place = [[A Coruña]] |occupation = Writer and literary critic |nationality = Spain |period = |website = https://miriambeizana.com }} '''Miriam Beizana Vigo''' ([[A Coruña]], 20 August 1990)<ref name="biografia">{{Cite web |url=https://miriambeizana.com/about/ |title=Sobre mí |trans-title=About me |access-date=10 March 2018 |last=Beizana Vigo |first=Miriam |website=MBV |place=A Coruña |language=Spanish}}</ref> is a Spanish writer and [[Literary criticism|literary critic]].
== Personal life and bibliography == She works in the administration oriented to the industrial sector, although he has been writing since he was very young.<ref name="biografia"/> Her first novel, ''Marafariña''.<ref name="marafariña1">{{Cite news |title=Miriam Beizana presentó "Marafariña" |trans-title=Miriam Beizana presented "Marafariña" |url=https://www.lavozdegalicia.es/noticia/carballo/carballo/2015/11/20/miriam-beizana-presento-marafarina/0003_201511C20C8993.htm |format=digital |newspaper=La Voz de Galicia |publication-date=20 November 2015 |access-date=10 March 2018 |language=Spanish|place=Carballo (A Coruña) }}</ref><ref name="videomarafariña">{{Cite AV media |title=Presentación de ''Marafariña'' en la Biblioteca de Carballo |trans-title=Presentation of ''Marafariña'' in the Library of Carballo |year=2015 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eaZzntv7wMc |via=YouTube |place=Carballo |access-date=10 March 2018 }}</ref>, partly autobiographical, tells the love story between Ruth, a young Jehovah's Witness and Olga, a Catalan girl who arrives in the village where the first one resides; his novel has a sequel, ''Inflorescence'', published 3 years later.<ref name="inflorescencia1">{{Cite news |first=Carla |last=Plumed |title=[Reseña] 'Inflorescencia' (Marafariña libro segundo) de Miriam Beizana Vigo |trans-title=[Review] 'Inflorescence' (Marafariña second book) by Miriam Beizana Vigo |url=http://www.cafedetinta.com/2018/07/resena-inflorescencia-marafarina-libro.html |format=digital |publication-date=2 July 2018 |access-date=15 July 2018 |language=Spanish |place=Café de tinta }}</ref> As for ''Todas las horas mueren'' (literally, ''All the hours die''), it is a short novel that, in the fiction, was written by Olga from some pages that her mother began. Finally, he wrote an essay about the pop singer [[Tino Casal]].<ref name="tinocasal1">{{Cite news |first=G. |last=D.R. |title=Tino Casal se asoma a LibrOviedo para contar 'tal como fue' |trans-title=Tino Casal looks at LibrOviedo to tell 'as he was' |url=http://www.elcomercio.es/oviedo/201605/09/tino-casal-asoma-libroviedo-20160509001720-v.html |format=digital |newspaper=El Comercio |publication-date=9 May 2016 |access-date=10 March 2018 |language=Spanish |place=Oviedo }}</ref><ref name="tinocasal2">{{Cite news |author=H., N. |title=Un Libroviedo de récords |trans-title=A LibrOviedo of records |url=http://www.lne.es/vida-y-estilo/gente/2016/05/16/libroviedo-records/1927409.html |format=digital |newspaper=La Nueva España |publication-date=16 May 2016 |access-date=10 March 2018 |language=Spanish |place=Oviedo }}</ref><ref name="videotinocasal">{{Cite AV media |title=''Tino Casal. Tal como fue''. Presentación del libro en la Sala Transcorrales |trans-title=''Tino Casal. As he was.'' Presentation of the book in the Transcorrales Room |year=2016 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zohGDh7VFUw |via=YouTube |place=Oviedo |access-date=10 March 2018 }}</ref>
Although in his work always gives prominence to women (usually lesbians), rejects the label of ''lesbian novels'' since her books are not exclusive of LGTBI people. In the words of the author:
{{quote|I think that no author or author writes LGBT novel itself. They write romance novel, fantasy novel, intimate novel, science fiction novel whose plot reflects a homosexual character. I do not know what kind of world we live in that makes this type of books have a distinctive, as if they could only focus on a general public. What anger. As if it were a problem, a barrier, a badge. How squeaky. Because I read more of a heterosexual novel than a lesbian novel, but it seems that the heterosexual world can not assume reading a lesbian novel.<ref name"novela lesbica">{{Cite news |first=Miriam |last=Beizana Vigo |title=Yo no escribo novela lésbica |trans-title=I do not write lesbian novel |url=https://miriambeizana.com/2017/11/22/yo-no-escribo-novela-lesbica/ |format=digital |newspaper=MBV |publication-date=22 November 2017 |access-date=15 July 2018 |language=Spanish}} </ref>}}
Among her influences are [[Fannie Flagg]], [[Virginia Woolf]], [[Carmen Laforet]], [[Rosa Montero]] and [[Ana María Matute]].
She collaborates in literary criticism on ''A Librería'' website,<ref name="alibreria">{{Cite web |url=https://alibreria.com/author/marafarinha/ |title=Literary critics by Miriam Beizana |access-date=10 March 2018 |last=Beizana Vigo |first=Miriam |format=digital |website=A Librería |language=Spanish}}</ref> and makes articles on the LGTB visibility and dissemination portal ''Hay una lesbiana en mi sopa'' (literally, ''There is a lesbian in my soup'').<ref name="hulems">{{Cite web |url=https://hayunalesbianaenmisopa.com/author/miriam-beizana/ |title=Articles by Miriam Beizana |access-date=15 July 2018 |last=Beizana Vigo |first=Miriam |format=digital |website=Hay una lesbiana en mi sopa |language=Spanish}}</ref>
